defaultCitizens Advice believes the Government proposals will have a negative impact on access to justice, with impli
defaultcations for compliance with Article 6 of the ECHR and also access to justice for those who 
defaulthave experienced breaches of other articles of the ECHR. The proposals could also have an impact on the ability of individuals to bring judicial reviews based wholly
default or partly on alleged breaches of the public sector equality duty (PSED) under the Equality Act 2010.
default&#xa0;
defaultEven unsuccessful judicial review cases have an impact. A
defaultwareness that decisions may be challenged by 
defaultjudicial review
default helps ensure decision-making is car
defaulteful, fair and reasonable
default. 
defaultVery few people can take the risk of bringing a claim for judicial review without the help of legal aid so it is public
defaultly
default funded judicial review claims that provide the necessary rigour to public decision making.
default&#xa0;
defaultStanding
default&#xa0;
defaultJudicial reviews brought by non government organisations (NGOs), charities, pressure groups and faith organisations are relatively successful compared to other types of judicial review, so clearly these successful cases are not simply publicity stunts. If 
defaulta case has no merit and is proposed purely to get a press release under the current system, it would not get any legal aid funding and the Government would not have to spend any taxpayers’ money defending it. The Government’s proposals will make no differe
defaultnce to the ability of campaigning organisations to put out press releases but would stop one of the most successful types of judicial review.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, we feel strongly that the lawfulness of public administration is the legitimate concern of the whole
default of society.
default 
defaultThe purpose of 
defaultj
defaultudicial 
defaultr
defaulteview is to address matters of public interest, not redress private wrongs. We believe any change to the rules on standing would distort the focus of 
defaultjudicial review
default, which is and should continue to be publicly minded 
defaultand forward looking
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultMany challenges
default 
defaultbrought in the public interest
default, regarding serious human rights issues,
default could not otherwise be brought by a claimant with a direct interest in the matter
default.
default 
defaultI
defaultn some cases those affected by a policy or decision cannot brin
defaultg a case themselve
defaults. As such there will be situations when the intervention of an organisation with a concern about a particular issue will be the only means to challenge unlawful practices. One example of this is where a Government policy is unlawful but 
defaulthas yet to impact on individuals. Another example is where the affected person is in no position to bring a judicial review, for instance, where they have been deported unlawfully. Challenge from an organisation can also be necessary where a defendant deci
defaultdes to settle cases with multiple individuals rather than cease the unlawful activities which affect many more. It will be detrimental to the rule of law to close off this avenue of challenge.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, many NGOs and charities are often ideally placed 
defaultto represent the interests of an affected group, can support their claim with specialist evidence and their presence lends an institutional overview to the issue. NGOs can also be well placed to judge which matters raise points of significant public import
defaultance, NGOs are able to observe patterns of repeated unlawfulness which collectively can be of great importance.
default 
defaultIt can also be more efficient for the court than dealing with a large number of individual cases. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhere a policy is being applied in a detrime
defaultntal way to a large number of people, it may take the intervention of an organisation to challenge the practice and if necessary take judicial review proceedings. Such action would be taken as a last resort but could be the only means to challenge the wide
defaultspread impact of potentially unlawful activities.
default&#xa0;
defaultA CAB in London
default saw
default a woman who, with her husband, had made a claim for 
defaultjobseekers allowance.
default 
defaultWhen h
defaulter husband 
defaultsubsequently
default started working
default, they immediately informed the 
defaultJobcentre and provided 
defaultpayslips as
default soon as they were issued. Despite 
defaultthis
default, 
defaultthe DWP decided to recover the overpayment of benefit and impose 
defaulta civil penalty
default on the mistaken grounds that they had failed to disclose a material fact
default. The couple were deeply unsettled by having a large debt 
defaultwhic
defaulth had arisen due to the Jobcentre’s failure to act on the information they provided. 
defaultThe civil penalty appeared to have been imposed without looking at all the evidence relating to the JSA claim.
default 
defaultThe 
defaultb
defaultureau believed that, if the application of civil penalt
defaulties in this way was found to be a blanket policy, 
defaultju
defaultdicial 
defaultr
defaulteview proceedings 
defaultcould
default be appropriate.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe constitutional role of charities, NGOs and other organisations in bringing 
defaultj
defaultudicial 
defaultr
defaulteview in the public interest is emphasized in case law.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe importance of setting the threshold for judicial review at a reasonable level was commented on in 
defaultR v Secretary of State for the Home Department, ex p 
defaultBulger
default 
default[2001] EWHC Admin 119 at 20
default ‘ the threshold for standing in judicial review has generally been
default set by the courts at a low level.  This…is because of the importance in public law that someone should be able to call decision makers to account’. 
default&#xa0;defaultThis is a particular issue where a regulator, for example, makes a decision which affects both individual
defaults and businesses. On their own, and without the support of third party organisations, individuals are unlikely to have the resources to take judicial review proceedings against a decision, whereas businesses with a contrary interest are more likely to use 
defaulttheir resources to bring in specialist legal teams, such as the 
defaultBritish Bankers Association (BBA)
default 
defaultv Financial Services Authority and Financial Ombudsman Service
default [2011] EWHC 999 which sought to challenge the FSA’s policy statement on PPI and the FOS online 
defaultresource which helped consumers make complaints about 
defaultmis
default-sold PPI. While the judgment in this case was beneficial for consumers, there is a risk that existing inequalities of power and resources could be exacerbated by the Government’s proposals with indi
defaultviduals losing any power or opportunity to challenge public decision making.
default&#xa0;
defaultInterveners
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government’s proposals to discourage organisations from intervening in cases, by imposing additional cost burdens on interveners, fail to recognise the public fo
defaultcus of judicial review. Where there are important matters of public policy, which may go beyond the particular interests of those involved in the claim, 
defaultintervener
defaults
default have particular expertise 
defaultthat
default contribute
defaults
default to a case and interventions can assist the court
default and improve the quality of decision making
default. 
default Government departments also intervene in cases themselves. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is no evidence that interventions generally add much, if anything, to the overall costs of a case and courts already have wide discretion as to
default the terms on which they allow interventions.
default Discouraging interveners by increasing the cost risk associated with intervening will discourage their participation and reduce the overall quality of judgments.  
default&#xa0;
defaultCosts
default&#xa0;
defaultWe believe the Government’s proposals 
defaulton costs would prevent many strong cases from ever being heard, limiting access to justice. This would cause significant injustices and do nothing to prevent weak cases blocking up the system. The Government has failed to show any evidence that there is a 
defaultproblem in the first place.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe difference between 
defaultj
defaultudicial 
defaultr
defaulteview and civil litigation stems from inequality of power (most cases are brought by individuals against the state), differences in purpose (
defaultj
defaultudicial 
defaultr
defaulteview is intended to prevent abuses of powe
defaultr by the state) and differences in procedure (very tight timescales for bringing a claim for 
defaultj
defaultudicial 
defaultr
defaulteview and no procedure under which claimants can inspect the documents held before deciding whether to proceed with a case). Therefore special costs rule
defaults are needed to protect claimants from potential financial ruin if a case is lost.
default&#xa0;defaultLimiting protective costs orders (PCOs) will prevent organisations acting in the public interest from accessing the courts.
default defaultInsufficient evidence has been provided as to th
defaulte scale of alleged detriment. 
defaultIncreasing the costs risk for claimants and legal representatives by restricting legal aid in cases where permission to apply for 
defaultjudicial review
default is not granted will prevent meritorious cases from being pursued and will allow 
defaultunfair, unlawful and unreasonable public decision making
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe proposals on standing combined with the proposals on PCOs risk creating a catch 22 situation where organisations that are able to show standing would be barred automatically from a PCO. PCOs ar
defaulte made where the proposed litigation is in the public interest. Individuals will be deterred from taking these important cases due to the risk of adverse costs, despite the public good that could stem from the action.
default&#xa0;
defaultEven when such cases are lost, there 
defaultis often benefit to the development of law by clarifying points. These cases can also confer benefit to public authorities by confirming the legality of their actions, helping to establish clearer guidance for good public administration.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe test proposed
default allows for no balancing of private interest and public benefit. Private interest can be slight but public benefit can be overwhelming. Lack of cost protection which deterred individuals from taking a case would have a detrimental impact on the wider publi
defaultc.
default&#xa0;
defaultFurthermore, the current consultation, 
defaultCost protection in defamation and privacy cases: the Government’s proposals
default, states, ‘The rationale for introducing cost protection is to ensure that meritorious cases are able to be brought or defended by the 
defaultless wealthy, who should not be deterred from bringing or defending an appropriate claim through fear of having to pay unaffordable legal costs to the other side if they lose’. We believe that there is a clear parallel to be drawn here. In defamation cases
default, there can often be a considerable power and financial imbalance between parties. This is also clearly the case of judicial reviews. The same deterrent to the bringing of appropriate cases will apply.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe do not believe that the case for change to wasted 
defaultcosts orders has been made. The courts already have the power to penalise representatives for improper, negligent or unreasonable conduct and do so where appropriate. Wasted costs orders are not an appropriate means to deal with litigation of weak cases. C
defaultlients can and sometimes do decide to continue with a case despite the advice from their legal representatives. They may be obliged to continue with a case in such circumstances due to their professional obligations. Widening the use of wasted cost orders 
defaultwill have a further chilling effect on the willingness of representatives to take on cases for clients of limited financial means.
defaultLegal aid payment for pre-permission work
default&#xa0;
defaultProposals to make payment for pre-permission legal aid work will reduce access 
defaultto judicial review as a remedy. Providers will be forced to shoulder all the risks of taking the case despite existing processes to prevent weak cases being funded.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LAA already conducts a merits assessment at each stage of provision of funding, usuall
defaulty requiring a barrister’s opinion on prospects. We believe that this provides sufficient protection to the public purse from weak cases.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe underpinning justification for this proposal is that the Government feels that too many weak cases are being funde
defaultd, but no statistical evidence has been put forward to support this. A case may be strong but may be withdrawn before the permission stage because the public body concerned provides an acceptable remedy to the applicant. In the experience of bureaux, issui
defaultng judicial review proceedings often has the effect of escalating an issue and ensuring a public body meets its obligations when negotiation has failed to do so.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition we believe that cases with significant merit will not be taken because of the unr
defaulteasonable burden of risk that would be placed upon representatives. Rather than weeding out weak cases, the proposals would in effect only fund the very strongest cases, those that representatives assessed as risk free as the case would be of a type where 
defaultthey would be certain that permission would be granted. In effect the bar for taking a case would be so high it would arguably be a poor use of tax payers’ money to defend a case which was so clear cut.
default&#xa0;
defaultMany of our advisers report that it is already very 
defaultdifficult to find legal aid lawyers to take on a judicial review because of the recent cuts to the legal aid budget. The remaining law centres and solicitor firms are working on an incredibly tight budget. Lawyers are therefore going to stop taking on judi
defaultcial review cases where there is some likelihood that they will not get paid for the work. Cases with merit, but with an element of uncertainty because, for example the law is developing or because further evidence needs to be obtained, will therefore be s
defaultcreened out of legal aid by representatives who simply cannot take the risk of not being paid.
default 
defaultThis will damage the development of case law and reduce the number of important test cases taken. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe do not believe that the new proposals will give practition
defaulters sufficient reassurance that they will be paid fairly for the work they undertake. First, it is impossible to tell in advance how the proposed LAA discretion will be applied in cases which are settled and second, practitioners will still need to risk su
defaultbstantial amounts on cases which are reasonably taken forward but which, for reasons outside of the control of the representative, may not progress beyond permission stage.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe claimant’s representative, will not necessarily be in the best position to jud
defaultge the merits of the case until further information is disclosed by the defendant.  In the majority of cases, it is the defendant who holds most of the crucial information with no compulsion to disclose it until forced to do so through the litigation proce
defaultss.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe principle of a discretionary scheme will add yet more uncertainty to the process and will require further work by the representative to make the application for payment (which will also itself be at risk of not being paid). It will also add a sign
defaultificant cost burden on the state for the extra administration for the LAA to do extra assessments on which cases deserve discretionary funding.
default&#xa0;
defaultA discretionary scheme is unlikely to be sufficient to allay fears that clients will find it much harder to fin
defaultd a lawyer willing to take on their case, due to the financial uncertainty entailed in the proposal.
default&#xa0;
defaultOne bureau reported that they have needed to find legal representation on a number of occasions to challenge a local authority’s refusal to accept their d
defaultuties to the children of asylum seekers. On each occasion the case was settled at the eleventh hour, almost on the steps of the court. On at least one occasion, this happened despite the local authority having received legal advice from its own legal depar
defaulttment to comply. These cases show that without adequate access to the courts, such practices can go unchallenged. The bureau is concerned that in future, legal representation will be significantly harder to secure, if the representative is uncertain whethe
defaultr they will be paid.
default&#xa0;
defaultCases which clarify the way that the state should treat large numbers of citizens beyond those who took the case may not find representation in future and cases which make an overwhelming impact for a single client might not be taken 
defaulton:
default&#xa0;
defaultA 
defaultCAB in the South East reported the case of a man who sought advice 
defaultafter 
defaulthis
default homelessness application had been turned down by their council
default, despite the fact he had no
defaultwhere to
default live and was suffering from a 
defaultserious lung condition.  Not only did the c
defaultouncil turn down the application but they also refused to house the 
defaultman
default whil
defaulte their decision was reviewed. 
defaultThe CAB 
defaultobtained
default a legal aid counsel opinion that they would be able to make an ap
defaultplication for judicial review. 
defaultWith the threat of this judicial rev
defaultiew the council agreed to provide
default accommodation pending review. 
defaultWith the CAB and 
defaultc
defaultounsel's opinion supporting the client, t
defaulthe review found in his favour, 
defaultthat 
defaulthe
default 
defaultwas
default in need of support to avoid homelessness and there wa
defaults no need for a court hearing. 
defaultIf the
default council had known that the CAB could not afford to take it further they may have been less likely to bow to pressure.
default&#xa0;
defaultA CAB in the North West advised a single homeless man. He had health issues and was vulnerable. The homeless section at the council had 
defaultrefused to take a homeless application from him and provide him with temporary accommodation while it was considered. The bureau attempted to resolve the issue without court action, but despite phone calls and a pre-action protocol letter, an agreement cou
defaultld not be reached. The bureau applied for legal aid on behalf of the man which enabled them to instruct counsel to prepare pleadings. Despite further calls explaining that the papers were ready to be issued at court, the council did not back down. An order
default was made that evening ex parte by the out of hours judge directing that he was to be given temporary accommodation. The judge's order was sent to the council who made arrangements to accommodate the client the same night, otherwise he would have been forc
defaulted to sleep rough.
default&#xa0;
defaultUnder the Government proposals, the bureau would have been at risk of not being paid for the work they carried out to ensure that the local authority accepted their duties to a vulnerable man.
default&#xa0;
defaultBorderline cases
default&#xa0;
defaultRemoving legal aid for b
defaultorderline cases is also a significant issue. Borderline in the context used by the LAA means around the 50 per cent potential success mark, and cases where borderline challenges are permitted currently include some public law, immigration and family claims
default. This means that around half of people who will no longer be able to afford to have their case heard would 
defaulthave won. They are often cases where the matters arising are fundamental ones, such as cases involving human rights. The very nature of a legal case
default is that the final outcome cannot be determined without deliberation on controversial issues. Test cases on borderline issues are often vital for shaping the development of the law and clarifying difficult questions. Removing this possibility will increase
default the power of public bodies and may allow undesirable practices to continue without a realistic option to challenge them.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government’s proposals will inhibit access to justice without achieving the stated aims of speed and efficiency
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultProcedural as o
defaultpposed to substantive defects in decisions
default&#xa0;defaultThe Government’s proposals to change the test that the court would apply in cases where claimants challenge procedural defects fails to appreciate the important role of judicial review in upholding the standards 
defaultof procedural fairness
default. The proposals
default 
defaultare
default likely to increase the burden on both claimants and defendants engaged in 
defaultj
defaultudicial 
defaultr
defaulteview proceedings and place the court in the shoes of the decision maker, a role in which it has no expertise.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn many cases 
defaultParliament has set out clearly what procedure Government bodies must take when making a decision to ensure they act lawfully. These changes mean that judges will have to decide whether or not the failure to follow the procedures set out by Parliament would
default have made any difference to Government bodies’ final decision.
default&#xa0;
defaultJudicial review is routinely concerned with challenges to the lawfulness of procedure. In general the 
defaultjudicial r
defaulteview court has no expertise to consider the merits of a decision. If the no di
defaultfference test was modified as proposed, it would involve the courts in matters it is ill-equipped to adjudicate on, adding to costs and requiring additional court time
default&#xa0;
defaultPermission hearings are shorter hearings where the evidence is not considered in depth.
default ‘No difference’ arguments heard later in the process often rely on extensive evidence. The Government proposals would increase the complexity of the permission stage by requiring more lengthy pleadings and it appears most likely that more cases will need 
defaultto be dealt with at an oral hearing. This would result in increased delays at this stage in the process and potentially increase the cost to tax payers.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, bringing forward ‘no difference’ arguments to the permission stage is likely to further 
defaultdisadvantage litigants in person (LIPs) who are often only able to secure (mostly pro bono) representation after the permission stage. Bringing forward such complex issues will make it harder for a LIP to progress a meritorious case. The Royal Courts of Ju
defaultstice Citizens Advice Bureau have identified that, of their client group of LIPs, 25 per cent have a protected characteristic. This suggests that the proposal would raise equality issues and therefore has human rights implications. We do not believe this p
defaultroposal is consistent with the UK’s duties under the ECHR.
default&#xa0;
defaultCoupled with proposals to restrict legal aid payments for permission work, this proposal would act as a serious disincentive for legal aid representatives when considering the risks of representat
defaultion.  Not only would further work be required at this early stage, which would be done at risk of non-payment, but the proposals would also introduce further uncertainty. Given the low levels of legal aid funding, we doubt whether many organisations with l
defaultegal aid funding will be able to do the initial work when there is a significant risk they will not be paid, even in a good case with a successful outcome for the client. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe public sector equality duty
default&#xa0;defaultCitizens Advice is a strong supporter of making th
defaulte 
defaultpublic sector equality duty (PSED)
default an essential tool of modern government
default. The PSED
default helps to ensure that the needs of different people are properly taken into account and balanced.
default 
defaultThe best alternative to having judicial reviews challenging 
defaultthe 
defaultPSED duty
default is for the Government to make sure these issues are considered 
defaultproperly 
defaultin the first place. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe objective behind the 
defaultPSED
default is to ensure that consideration of equality forms part of the day-to-day decision-making and operational delivery of public bodies.
default This is as vital now as ever, given that all public authorities are having to make difficult decisions about how to prioritise their scarce resources. From our experience it is clear that is not happening
default,
default which is why judicial review is needed on PSED is
defaultsues. 
defaultWe also believe that the rights protected by the PSED are of such importance that judicial review should be retained as the remedy for any breaches.
default 
defaultJudicial review can achieve far reaching improvements for large numbers of people who might otherwise
default be subject to discrimination.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe have considered whether there might be a viable alternative to judicial review and do not believe a workable alternative exists.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the case
default below
default, litigation was necessary to secure adherence to the PSED.
default&#xa0;
defaultA CAB in 
defaultthe 
defaultNorth West
default pursued a complaint about a care package for 
defaulta woman
default who was bedbound and needed a hoist to get out of bed with carers attending four times a day to change her incontinence pads. She had dementia, neuropathy, incontinence and was unable to stand
default. Under the NHS funded care package, the 
defaultprimary care trust (PCT)
default insisted that they could only provide 
defaultthree
default pads per day
default, 
defaultnot enough in this case. The client could not meet the extra cost of additional pads. The bureau advised that the care package shoul
defaultd meet the cost of however many pads were required and 
defaultcomplaint on the woman’s behalf
default, but the NHS 
defaultclaimed
default they were following their own policy to only allow three pads per day. After further advocacy by the bureau, the NHS incontinence team re-assessed t
defaulthe client and agreed to allow four pads. Although the client received a positive outcome to her individual case, the NHS would not amend their policy so that others need not face the same or similar disadvantage and barriers to getting their basic human ne
defaulteds met. The bureau threatened judicial review, which cited amongst other legal provisions the 
defaultPSED
default. Following litigation in 2012 the NHS changed the policy so that everyone will now be assessed on their own individual needs.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe combined effect of legal 
defaultaid proposals
default&#xa0;defaultPrevious changes to legal aid have had the effect of reducing the advice and support available to individuals. Social welfare law raises complex legal issues and problems are often extremely serious to users of the justice system. Limiting t
defaulthe scope of issues with which legal aid funded advisers can help means they are not able to solve people’s problems fully, as many clients experience multiple problems across different civil justice and social welfare scope areas.
default&#xa0;
defaultReductions in legal aid 
defaulthave meant that many people have been unable to access the specialist support they need. Limiting the availability of legal aid for judicial review will seriously restrict availability of judicial review as a means of challenge for many people, leaving the
defaultm powerless to challenge public decisions that have a material effect on their lives.
